explanation:
To decide whether any statements in OS_SocketGetInfo are dead (i.e. could be removed without changing program behaviour) the analyzer needs the following information:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro/function can change control flow (e.g. return an error, assert, or call logging). If it aborts/returns on a NULL pointer then later code would be unreachable/never executed; if it only logs then it does not prevent execution. Its behavior is essential to know whether the function body can run.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The if-block depends entirely on this call returning OS_SUCCESS. Whether the block is ever entered (and under what conditions) depends on this function’s semantics, possible side effects, and how it sets the token. If this function never returns OS_SUCCESS for some inputs then the block is dead.

- OS_SUCCESS: The concrete value/meaning used to test success is needed to interpret OS_ObjectIdGetById results.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE and OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL: These parameters affect OS_ObjectIdGetById behavior (which object set and lock mode are queried). Their definitions may change whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can succeed in practice.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type and its semantics (ownership, validity) are required to know whether subsequent operations using the token are meaningful or have side effects.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET and OS_global_stream_table: The macro and the global table are used to obtain the record pointer. To know whether reading record fields has effects or whether the macro can have side effects (bounds checks, logging) the definitions are required. Also needed to determine whether the assignment to sock_prop copies meaningful data or is redundant.

- OS_common_record_t: The structure fields (name_entry, creator, etc.) and whether accessing them has side effects (or is e.g. always constant) are necessary to determine if copying from record changes program behaviour.

- OS_socket_prop_t: The layout and semantics of the destination object (sock_prop->name, creator) are required to know whether the memset and strncpy/do assignment are necessary initializations or redundant writes (i.e. whether their removal would affect observable state).

- OS_SocketGetInfo_Impl: This call may perform additional observable work (e.g. fill more fields, perform logging, trigger side effects). If it is a no-op then the call may be dead; if it has side effects then it is essential code. Its implementation is therefore required.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releasing the token may have observable side effects (resource release, unlocking, reference count changes). Whether the release is necessary to program behaviour must be known to decide if it is dead.

- strncpy and memset: These routines (and how they are used here) affect the visible state of *sock_prop. If they are no-ops (because sock_prop is overwritten later by Impl) they could be dead; otherwise they are required initialization. Their semantics (e.g. null-termination behavior) matter for deciding dead assignments.

In summary, to prove that any specific assignment, call, or release in OS_SocketGetInfo is dead you must know (a) whether the conditional is ever true (OS_ObjectIdGetById and related constants), (b) whether each operation has observable side effects (OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET, record and socket struct definitions, OS_SocketGetInfo_Impl, OS_ObjectIdRelease), and (c) whether initializations/assignments (memset/strncpy) are later used or redundant. The symbols above are the minimal set required to make that determination.
